#1 Ascending colonic adenocarcinoma, near obstructing
#2 Acute-on-chronic microcytic iron-deficiency anemia status-post 4 units of blood transfusion
#3 Multiple (`R` 10) low-attenuation hepatic masses concerning for metastases, largest 3 x 3-cm in size
#4 Large cystic left adnexal mass
#5 Hypertension
#6 Migraines
Ms. Gentry is a 43-year-old female with a history of microcytic anemia who was recently-diagnosed to have a colonic mass and was biopsy-proven adenocarcinoma.  Imaging has revealed metastases to the liver, as well as retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy.  In addition, an adnexal mass was noted.  Most recently she has had acute worsening of anemia and has required 4 units of blood transfusion.  She complains of intermittent dark stools.  We believe that she needs to undergo surgical resection before proceeding for chemotherapy because of the size of the lesion which is at high-risk for complete obstruction, as well as recent acute GI bleeding.   For the same, we will schedule a consultation with Dr. Smith.  In addition, we will also have her see Dr. Mefford in Medical Oncology which is scheduled for tomorrow morning.  We also discussed HNPCC, its work-up and its implications for family members.  She is interested in pursuing work-up for that.  To begin we will obtain IHC and MSI for DNA mismatch repair on the biopsy specimens from colonoscopy done on February 3.  If those are concerning then we will schedule consultation with our Medical Genetics department.
We will also schedule ovarian ultrasound for the large cystic adnexal mass.  Recent set of blood tests and chest x-ray have been done in anticipation of surgery.  I will revisit with Ms. Gentry along with our surgery colleagues tomorrow.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.
Discussed and seen with Dr. Alejandre.

