[start section id="20103"]

Ms. Gentry is a 43-year-old female who is a resident of Nisula and was admitted to the GI-B Service at Vielmetti Hospital a few weeks ago where I saw her.  She was admitted for diarrhea, microcytic iron-deficiency anemia, and questionable GI bleeding.  During her hospitalization an EGD was done which was unremarkable.  She was set-up for an outpatient colonoscopy.  The colonoscopy revealed large ascending colonic mass which was confirmed with biopsy as invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma.  During her hospitalization she dropped her hemoglobin to 6.9 and was transfused 4 units of blood.  She has been on iron supplements and has been having intermittent dark stools, but no frank hematochezia.  She has no family history of first or second-degree relatives with colon cancer.  A third-degree relative was diagnosed with colon cancer at more than 50 years of age.  No history of ovarian or breast cancer.  She has three children of ages 21, 20, and 19.  She denies weight-loss.  She denies fevers or chills.
She was seen by Dr. Cuneo this morning and underwent a CT abdomen and pelvis for staging purposes.  The CT-scan revealed multiple hepatic low-attenuation lesions in both hepatic lobes, as well as in the caudate lobe worrisome for metastases.  The one in the caudate lobe was largest and 3.3 x 2.7 x 3.1 cm in size.  Single enlarged retroperitoneal lymphadenopathy about 1-cm in size, and a 6-mm node in the right lower quadrant was seen.  In addition, the large colonic mass about 7.1 x 7.7 x 9.1 cm was seen in the ascending colon.  There was also a large left adnexal cystic mass measuring 5.4 x 4.8 x 6.3 cm in size.
She denies any fever, chills or bowel obstructive symptoms.

[end section id="20103"]

